    {
        "header": "1Introduction",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2607.05392/2607.05392v1/images/teaser.jpg",
                "caption": "Figure 1:Diverse 3D worlds of arbitrary size and complexity are easily created withSynCity 3000from scratch.\nOur approach first constructs a visually and semantically coherent 2D template of the entire scene, and then converts it into 3D Gaussian Splats with a fine-tuned two-stage generative diffusion model.",
                "position": 335
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "header": "2Related work",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2607.05392/2607.05392v1/images/2d-gen.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:2D Generation Pipeline.We generate a dimetric scene template based on text prompts and optional layout constraints. After subdividing the latents into windows, we apply a latent diffusion model to jointly denoise the latent canvas. Once complete, the latent canvas is then decoded into the final 2D scene template.",
                "position": 423
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "header": "3Method",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2607.05392/2607.05392v1/images/inference.png",
                "caption": "Figure 3:3D Generation Pipeline.We use a multi-stage pipeline to synthesize full 3D scenes from 2D templates using convolutional inference.\nIn this inference process, we divide the latent into smaller regions that we jointly denoise.\nEach region has a direct template correspondence.\nTo transform a scene, we first synthesize the sparse structure—a coarse voxel grid.\nThen, we infer features that encode the appearance and semantics of each voxel.\nFinally, we decode these structured latents into the final 3D Gaussian Splats representation.\nWe use the decoders of[62].",
                "position": 506
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2607.05392/2607.05392v1/images/train.png",
                "caption": "Figure 4:Fine-Tuning Design.We utilize two objectives in our fine-tuning process.\nIn the first (top), we provide the coreandsurrounding context to the model.\nIn the second (bottom), we only provide the core, which imitates the original objective of TRELLIS[62].\nIn both cases, we use a masked conditioning image and apply the loss only to the core.",
                "position": 516
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "header": "4Dataset",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2607.05392/2607.05392v1/images/dataset.png",
                "caption": "Figure 5:Data Generation.We propose a dataset engine to generate diverse 3D scenes by placing random Objaverse-XL[14]objects on randomized terrains.\nEach scene is rendered in dimetric projection to match the 2D template generationFig.˜2.\nThe rendering of the scene is masked to only show the core, whereas we crop the 3D scene to include the core and some context.\nThis 3D crop is then converted into a voxel grid and infused with DINOv2[44]features.\nWe then encode it into sparse structure and structured latents using the encoders of[62].",
                "position": 654
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "header": "5Experiments",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2607.05392/2607.05392v1/images/comparisons/syncity_comparison_flattened.jpg",
                "caption": "Figure 6:Comparison With SynCity[15].We compare scenes generated by SynCity (left) and our method (right) using the same prompt for each. Overall, the worlds generated by our method are richer, more vibrant, and more coherent, both visually and semantically. They have an organic structure that lets elements flow across the whole scene.",
                "position": 797
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2607.05392/2607.05392v1/images/comparisons/large-scene.jpg",
                "caption": "Figure 7:Large Scene Detail Comparison.We let both our method (top) and TRELLIS (right) reconstruct a larger scene (3136×15683136\\times 1568pixels template, left).\nWhile the overall scene produced by TRELLIS looks decent, its resolution notably impacts its capability to reproduce details.\nMeanwhile,SynCity 3000has a high adherence to the template and reproduces details more faithfully.\nWe recommend viewing on a display and zooming in.",
                "position": 944
            }
        ]
    },
